{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609780"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:50:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:50:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16119"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16119"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.35,0.1,0.25,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8810"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63966"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8810"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16119"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49396"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8686"},{"type":"tags","id":"8692"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21024"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21027"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63966"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, all human embryos possess identical external genital structures regardless of their genetic sex.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes when visible sexual differentiation of external genitalia first begins?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["After week 7","After week 8","After week 9","After week 10","After week 11"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPrior to \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek 7\u003C/strong\u003E, all embryos have identical external genital structures in what is known as the indifferent stage. During this period, embryos possess a genital tubercle, paired urogenital folds, and paired labioscrotal swellings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek 8\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek 9\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek 10\u003C/strong\u003E, or \u003Cstrong\u003Eweek 11\u003C/strong\u003E would be too late, as sexual differentiation has already begun. Under the influence of dihydrotestosterone in males, the genital tubercle elongates to form the penis, the urogenital folds fuse to form the penile urethra, and the labioscrotal swellings fuse to form the scrotum. In females without androgens, these structures develop into the clitoris, labia minora, and labia majora respectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis process of sexual differentiation is dependent on the presence or absence of androgens, particularly dihydrotestosterone, which is produced in greater quantities in male embryos after week 7.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["External genitalia remain morphologically identical in male and female embryos until week 7 of development.","Sexual differentiation of external genitalia begins after week 7 under the influence of androgens in males.","The genital tubercle, urogenital folds, and labioscrotal swellings are present in all embryos during the indifferent stage."],"references":["Cunha GR, Robboy SJ, Kurita T, Isaacson D, Shen J, Cao M, Baskin LS. Development of the human female reproductive tract. Differentiation. 2018 Sep-Oct;103:46-65. doi: 10.1016/j.diff.2018.09.001. Epub 2018 Sep 6. PMID: 30236463; PMCID: PMC6234064.","Sajjad Y. Development of the genital ducts and external genitalia in the early human embryo. J Obstet Gynaecol Res. 2010 Oct;36(5):929-37. doi: 10.1111/j.1447-0756.2010.01272.x. Epub 2010 Sep 16. PMID: 20846260.","P A A, Arbor TC, Krishan K. Embryology, Sexual Development. [Updated 2023 Aug 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557601/","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49396"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16119"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49396"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T20:26:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T20:27:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8810"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63966"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"t